I first did this my second semester of college back when i was in 170... funnily enough, a few months ago I was cleaning out my room, found a wrinkled piece of paper, and unraveled it to find a correct prediction of exactly how the last 2 years of my life had gone... It was pretty scary. 

Though it may be effective at predicting outcomes, there is a key flaw... humans are particularly bad at knowing what will make them happy/what they want. Especially in college, you should be expanding your perspectives, definitions of success, and desirable futures. Following some plan you made as a 18/19 year-old just feels silly when you're 21. So i'd say be careful? Don't feel tied down to decisions you made a long time ago, and embrace change?
<@U03KC99B6> Thanks for this up! How long have you been implementing this type of process? And have you found it to pan out well?

To be honest, it's a bit silly to expect that such a decision tree can extrapolate to life, but it can help you think about your near-term actions in a broader context, think about probabilities and outcomes somewhat realistically, and give you the sense that everything is being done for a reason... it's really hard to keep track of all of those things in your head as you're evaluating different futures and often ends up in making costly mistakes.

I'd say generally I don't have much of a process, one silly/quirky thing that I have a tendency of doing is a `Decision Tree.` I pull out the trusty whiteboard and draw a node that represents myself in the present moment. From that node I draw several lines out to several decisions I could make about the near-term future, with a particular scope - for instance, if the scope was *professional life* I would draw lines to new nodes: "Focus on Getting Good Grades", "Spend time on Passion Project", and "Practice for Interviews and Apply to Jobs"... These options should be (mostly) mutually exclusive, and be roughly equivalent in time and money expenditure. 

From each of the newly formed nodes, I then connect lines to several more nodes. These should be potential consequences of each action taken, annotated with rough probabilities. For instance, from "Focus on Getting Good Grades" I might draw "Get Recommendation Letter - 50%", "Score Directed Research - 10%", "Get All A's - 20%" note that the probabilities shouldn't to add up to 100% and that they aren't mutually exclusive. Then from each array of outcomes, I take combinations of outcomes and draw out further Decisions that need to be made assuming that those decisions are made... for instance, assuming that the following conditions are met (Directed Research, All A's, and Recommendation Letter), I draw out the following decisions "Apply to PhD" "Apply to Masters Program" "Apply for a Research-y Job" etc... and repeat the process as described. I do this for all branches of the decision tree, until I hit about 3 years out (MAX), and then stop, look at which possibilities I would respect the most, given my current values, and pick the near-term decision which would lead me to that path.

`Does freewill exist?` This depends on your definition of freewill... but if we take it in the sense of the word of your "spirit" "soul" "consciousness" having influence over your subsequent actions, the answer seems to be a mournful *no* according to most scientific explorations. As for a philosophical view, Camus has an interesting view of freewill that i've latched on to in recent years, explained in his _Myth of Sisyphus_  in the section called *Absurd Freedom*. It's the concept of *practical freewill* ... 

```Knowing whether or not man is free doesn’t interest me. I can experience only my own freedom. As to it, I can have no general notions, but merely a few clear insights. The problem of “freedom as such” has no meaning.```

<https://sparksc.slack.com/archives/C7524DAHW/p1507236571000176> -- <@U03KA9P37> The answer for me, seems to be a resounding `both`. As for "Which space does it impact more/What realm do you tackle the problem in?" This is where it gets tricky. Poverty falls under the category of a *wicked problem* in my opinion ( <http://www.crop.org/CROPNewsEvents/Poverty-as-a-wicked-problem.aspx> ), which makes it seem like there is no _right_ answer to this question. I think it can be argued equally well, that change must first start in the cultural, or economic realm first. 

My personal opinion is that given that our metrics/methods of determining *progress* in the cultural realm are *far less advanced* than those of the economic realm, we should tackle this problem first as an economic problem, with mind to how the cultural underpinnings of this problem are being addressed/not-addressed when evaluating among different economic solutions.
